University of St. Thomas School of Law

UNIVERSITY OF ST. THOMAS

SCHOOL OF LAW

SATURDAY, MAY 16, 2020 MINNEAPOLIS, MN

FROM THE DEAN

Today we celebrate the graduation of St. Thomas Lawâs Class of 2020. We are not (yet) able to gather in person to mark the occasion, but that does not diminish our pride in the achievements of these remarkable graduates. The degrees these graduates have earned are a credit to their hard work and the dedication of a faculty and staff deeply committed to their success. Of course, the support of family and friends has also played an immeasurable role. Thanks to the parents, loved ones and friends who have traveled this journey with them. At St. Thomas Law, we prepare our students for a cause greater than themselves. That cause is captured best by the term âsolidarity,â and it shows up in our law school as a shared vision of the common good; a commitment to social justice, service and community; and a level of excellence in teaching and mentoring that prepares students to become accomplished servant leaders. Given the challenges they have faced this year, the Class of 2020 has demonstrated the power of solidarity like no other class in our schoolâs history. We are grateful for the many ways the Class of 2020 has contributed to St. Thomas Law â our community would not be the same without you.

Congratulations, and thank you.

Robert K. Vischer Dean and Mengler Chair in Law

PUBLIC SERVICE

Each of todayâs J.D. graduates has completed at least 50 hours of community service work as part of his or her legal education at the University of St. Thomas School of Law. The public service requirement is fashioned on the belief that all lawyers â and for that matter all people â have an obligation to share the gifts with which they have been blessed. The class as a whole completed more than 9,800 hours of community service work. For the students listed below, public service is clearly more than a requirement for graduation. The number of service hours each recorded over his or her three years of law school is inspiring and extraordinary. It is fitting that their accomplishments should be recognized today.

MISSION AWARDS

The University of St. Thomas School of Law, as a Catholic law school, is dedicated to integrating faith and reason in the search for truth through a focus on morality and social justice. To advance this mission, each member of the law school community is dedicated to promoting excellence in professional preparation, scholarly engagement and societal reform, and service and community. Each year, St. Thomas Law celebrates involvement and leadership in activities that support the schoolâs mission through its annual Living the Mission Awards. One member of each class who best exemplifies the mission, both in and out of the classroom, is presented with an overall Living the Mission Award. Awards are also presented for Excellence in Professional Preparation, Scholarly Engagement and Societal Reform, and Service and Community. Congratulations to the members of our 2020 graduating classes who have been honored with Mission Awards during their law school careers.
